08853nam a22011895i 9780823289134DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232891347 a10.1515/97808232891342doi  a(DE-B1597)577740  a(OCoLC)1237409964  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aN6655.5.C63bF67 2021 7aART0151102bisacsh04a709.8122300aForm and Feeling :bThe Making of Concretism in Brazil /ced. by Antonio Sergio Bessa. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b96 b/w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForm and Feeling -- tPosteverything—An Introduction -- tI -- t1. Architectural Mechanisms and Body Techniques: The Experiências of Flávio de Carvalho -- t2. Form and Sensibility: Discursive Discrepancies in Concrete and Neoconcrete Art -- t3. The Bauhaus in Brazil: Pedagogy and Practice -- t4. Grundlehre at the Ulm School of Design: A Survey of Basic Design Teaching -- t5. Twisting the Modernist Curve: Mary Vieira’s Polyvolume: Meeting Point -- t6. Lina Bo Bardi and the Creation of the School of Visual Arts in Parque Lage -- tII -- t7. Tropical Reason: The Making of a Counterculture in Brazil -- t8. Epidermal and Visceral Works: Lygia Pape and Anna Maria Maiolino -- t9. Word-Drool: The Constructive Secretions of Lygia Clark -- t10. Emil Forman: Removing the Silence of Things -- t11. The Funeral of Brazilian Modernism: Glauber Rocha and the Death of Di Cavalcanti -- tIII -- t12. Favela Noh: Haroldo de Campos and Hélio Oiticica at the Chelsea Hotel -- t13. Retrieval of the Unreadable: Arno Holz and Sousândrade Revisited by Augusto and Haroldo de Campos -- t14. The Wanderer, the Earth: Nature and History in the Work of Sousândrade and Paulo Nazareth -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA significant contribution on the development and aftermath of post–World War II Concretism in BrazilForm and Feeling features a collection of essays by noted scholars exploring the sensorial, experience-based, and participatory practices pioneered in the 1950s by artists and poets such as Flávio de Carvalho, Ivan Serpa, Hélio Oiticica, Haroldo de Campos, Mary Vieira, Lygia Pape, Anna Maria Maiolino, Lygia Clark, Waly Salomão, and Emil Forman, among many others. Fourteen thought-provoking essays examine how many of their strategies constituted a pertinent critique of the country’s wide-ranging embrace of Eurocentric modernity while anticipating a number of practices prevalent among contemporary artists today—namely, the rise of art as social practice, the embrace of pedagogical concerns by artists, and relational aesthetics.The fourteen essays collected in this volume consider the ramifications of modernist abstraction in the second half of the twentieth century and contribute to a growing academic field in postwar Brazilian and Latin American art history. Contributions to this anthology examine the development of modernist ideas that flourished in Brazil during a controversial period interspersed by dictatorial regimes. The global aspect of Brazilian art is especially evident in these studies, presenting the relational complexity of their subjects as transcultural, transnational actors while simultaneously contributing to a growing, increasingly nuanced understanding of visual and material culture, performance, and criticism in Brazil.Form and Feeling continues the important process of re-analyzing the intersections of Concretism and Neo concretism, arguing for greater affinities between the primary and lesser-known cast of characters while equally redistributing the strict geographical divisions of São Paulo and Rio de Janeiro. This anthology broadly situates this extraordinary period of artistic experimentation in direct relationship to contemporary factors, such as psychoanalysis, educational systems, poetry, politics, and feminism. It crafts innovative relationships about the constructive hierarchies of form and space, poetry and painting, and mathematics and philosophy, thus engendering new positions for a deeply ensconced period in Brazilian history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArt, Braziliany20th century. 0aConcrete artzBrazil. 4aArt & Visual Culture. 4aLatin American Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh  aConcretism.  aHaroldo de Campos.  aHélio Oiticica.  aLygia Clark.  aLygia Pape.  aNeo-concretism.  aSousândrade.1 aAsbury, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsbury, Michael.1 aBessa, Antonio Sergio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBessa, Antonio Sergio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBessa, Antonio Sergio.1 aCalirman, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalirman, Claudia.1 aCoelho, Frederico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoelho, Frederico.1 aGonçalves, Marcos Augusto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonçalves, Marcos.1 aHomem de Mello, Simone.1 aLira, Jose.1 aLira, José T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLopes, Fernanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLopes, Fernanda.1 aMello, Simone Homem de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMäntele, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMäntele, Martin.1 aNelson, Adele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat